<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-070-124  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 070 124.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 20 1989 v23 n7 p68(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Besting two barriers to IS planning. (information systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stevens, Larry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The two major hurdles that can surface when creating andimplementing a strategic plan for information systems are: gainingthe cooperation from end users, who can create major obstructionsduring the formulation phase; and securing support from topmanagement at the implementation stage.andP;  DMR Group Inc Dir MichaelAnderson says methods to reduce resistance in both instances is toemphasize modularity and flexibility in plans and to considersetting up a broad long-range plan of three to five yearsdelineating the company's direction, a middle-range plan of two tofour years containing some technologies the company may beseriously considering purchasing and a one- to two-year plan thatis actively being implemented.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information SystemsStrategic planningCooperationEnd UsersManagement-EDP Relations.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>